et Union combines textual and visual analysis, as well as archival research to highlight the multiple narratives that contributed to rebuilding military identities. Each chapter visits a particular site of this reconstruction, including debates about conscription and evasion, appropriate role models for cadets, misogynist military imagery in cartoons, the fraught militarized workplaces of nuclear physicists, and the first cohort of cosmonauts, who represented the completion of the project to rebuild militarized masculinity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMasculinityzSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aMenzSoviet UnionxIdentityxHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitarismzSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aWWII.  aWorld War II.  acartoons.  acold war.  aconscription.  acosmonauts.  amasculinity.  amilitary.  anuclear physicists.  asoldiers.  asoviet union.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262471940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442624719423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442624719.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles